"""
MKT Context Commentary — Romans chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-romans-1-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/romans.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (contested terms)
- data/translation/notes/romans.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/romans.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/romans.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Romans 1:18-32 is read against Wisdom of Solomon 11-15 as the assumed Jewish polemic
  against Gentile idolatry that Paul's audience would recognize
- The "diatribe" (διατριβή) style of 2:1ff is flagged as a recognized rhetorical form;
  the imaginary interlocutor is progressively revealed as a Torah-confident Jew by 2:17
- hilastērion (3:25) is contextualized primarily via LXX/Day of Atonement imagery,
  with the "public display" contrast to the hidden mercy seat noted
- "Grace and peace" salutation is treated as a deliberate Jewish-Hellenistic hybrid
- The Shema (Deut 6:4) is identified as the theological foundation for 3:29-30
- The catena of OT citations in 3:10-18 is identified as haraz (string-citation technique)
  common in Second Temple and rabbinic exegesis
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>Paul writes to a congregation he did not found and has never visited. The letter opening follows the standard Greco-Roman epistolary form (<em>sender — recipient — greeting</em>), but Paul extends the identification of sender across seven verses, embedding his theological agenda in the salutation itself. Ancient letters were meant to substitute for the physical presence of the sender; the extended opening signals that Paul wants the Roman Christians to hear his full theological self-introduction before he arrives in person.</p><p>Self-description as <em>doulos</em> (slave) of Christ would have carried a double register for Roman readers. In Roman society, high-status imperial slaves (<em>familia Caesaris</em>) could hold positions of enormous administrative power; being the slave of a great master was not inherently demeaning. At the same time, the title "slave of the Lord" was conventional for Israel\'s prophets (Moses, David, the prophets) — a resonance Paul\'s Jewish readers would catch immediately.</p>',

    "2": '<p>Paul insists the gospel is not a novelty but the fulfillment of Israel\'s own scriptures. This matters for the Roman congregation, which included Jewish Christians who would be suspicious of a message that appeared to abandon their heritage. "Promised beforehand" (<em>proepēngeilato</em>) positions God as a faithful covenant partner who has now delivered on prior commitments. The emphasis on "holy scriptures" underscores that the Hebrew writings were not merely human documents but vehicles of divine promise.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"As to his earthly life" (<em>kata sarka</em>, lit. "according to the flesh") — the phrase does not demean the incarnation but specifies the sphere of assessment: judged by ordinary human descent, Jesus belongs to David\'s line. Davidic descent was the defining credential for messianic legitimacy, based on the Nathan oracle (2 Sam 7:12-16) and on prophetic passages like Isa 11:1 and Jer 23:5. Second Temple Jews expected a Davidic king who would restore Israel\'s sovereignty; Paul immediately signals that this expectation is both fulfilled and re-defined.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"The Spirit of holiness" (<em>pneuma hagiōsynēs</em>) is a Hebrew-inflected phrase (cf. Ps 51:11, ruach qodshekha) rather than the more typical Greek <em>pneuma hagion</em>. It signals the divine sphere in contrast to the fleshly sphere of v. 3. "Appointed the Son of God in power by his resurrection" — <em>horizō</em> means "defined, designated, publicly marked out." The resurrection is not when Jesus became God\'s Son but when he was declared to be what he had always been, now with vindicating power. This is among the earliest crystallized formulas in the NT.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"Obedience of faith" (<em>hypakoē pisteōs</em>) — possibly a genitive of apposition ("obedience that consists in faith") or of source ("obedience arising from faith"). Paul\'s apostolic mission was to bring <em>all the Gentiles</em> into this covenant loyalty. This was a socially radical claim: Jewish missionary activity generally converted individuals; Paul envisions an empire-wide transformation of covenant membership. The phrase "for his name\'s sake" frames the mission in terms of honor — the reputation of the God of Israel among the nations.</p>',

    "6": '<p>The Roman congregation was not Paul\'s mission territory, which is partly why he must establish his apostolic credentials so carefully. The Roman church had apparently grown from Jewish Christians who had been in Jerusalem at Pentecost (Acts 2:10 mentions "visitors from Rome") and returned home as believers. The congregation likely met in house churches (cf. the greetings in ch. 16) scattered across a city of perhaps 1 million people.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The salutation "grace and peace" (<em>charis kai eirēnē</em>) is a Hellenistic-Jewish hybrid. <em>Charis</em> adapts the standard Greek letter greeting <em>chairein</em> ("greetings") while infusing it with the theological meaning of unearned divine favor. <em>Eirēnē</em> renders the Hebrew <em>shalom</em> — not merely the absence of conflict but the comprehensive well-being of covenantal restoration. Paul applies this formula to Roman citizens who live in the shadow of the <em>Pax Romana</em>, the empire\'s version of peace enforced by military power.</p><p>"Called to be his holy people" — <em>klētois hagiois</em>, "called holy ones." The language of calling and holiness was Israel\'s own (cf. Exod 19:6, "a kingdom of priests and a holy nation"). Paul applies it without hesitation to a Gentile-inclusive congregation.</p>',

    "8": '<p>Thanksgiving formulas were conventional in Greco-Roman letters, but Paul adapts them to function theologically. The Roman church\'s faith being "reported all over the world" would have been a genuine statement — Rome was the communication hub of the empire, and news from Rome circulated throughout the Mediterranean. In a culture built on honor and reputation, a community known for its faith had social standing.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"Whom I serve in my spirit in preaching the gospel of his Son" — Paul uses <em>latreuō</em>, the Greek word for priestly/temple service (cf. Heb 9:9; Luke 2:37). He frames his missionary work as liturgical offering. This is significant: Paul has no temple, no sacrifice, no priesthood in the conventional sense — yet he presents his apostolic labor in the vocabulary of worship, a claim he expands in 15:16 where he calls himself a "priest of the gospel."</p>',

    "10": '<p>Paul\'s repeated attempts to visit Rome had been blocked — by what he calls "a hindrance" in 15:22 (likely his obligations to complete his mission in the eastern Mediterranean). The language of prayer and divine will reflects the practical theology of mission: Paul plans, but God opens or closes the way. This is not resignation but trust in the larger pattern of God\'s redemptive timeline.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"Some spiritual gift" (<em>charisma pneumatikon</em>) — Paul is careful not to specify what this gift would be, perhaps to avoid appearing presumptuous toward a congregation he has not founded. The language of "making strong" (<em>stērizō</em>) was used of military reinforcement and structural support — the congregation needs to be established for the demands ahead.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"That you and I may be mutually encouraged" — Paul corrects his first statement (v. 11) in real time, adding the reciprocal dimension. This is not mere politeness. In the patron-client culture of Rome, teachers typically flowed benefit downward to recipients; Paul refuses this hierarchy by positioning the relationship as mutual. The Roman Christians will teach him as much as he teaches them.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"Brothers and sisters" — the fictive kinship language of early Christianity was socially disruptive in a world organized by actual family networks and patronage chains. Calling people "brother" and "sister" across social, ethnic, and class boundaries signaled a new kind of community. Paul\'s plans to "have a harvest" (<em>karpon</em>) among the Romans uses an agricultural metaphor for the results of his missionary work — the language of productivity that the Roman world would recognize.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"Greeks and non-Greeks, wise and foolish" — in the Greek-speaking world, <em>barbaros</em> (barbarian) was purely a linguistic category: those who did not speak Greek (the word likely derived from the sound of non-Greek speech, <em>bar-bar</em>). It carried cultural connotations of being uneducated in Hellenistic philosophy and rhetoric. "Wise and foolish" (<em>sophois kai anoētois</em>) adds an intellectual register — Paul\'s obligation extends across both the philosophical elite and the uneducated masses. Rome was a cosmopolitan city that included all of these groups.</p>',

    "15": '<p>Paul\'s eagerness to preach in Rome is notable given Roman Christians already exist. He is not coming to found a church but to strengthen and then launch outward from it (see 15:24, 28 — Spain as his ultimate destination). Rome is geographically and politically the western terminus of the empire; it serves as the strategic base for the western mission, just as Antioch served for the eastern.</p>',

    "16": '<p>Crucifixion was, in Roman legal and social terms, the most shameful form of execution — reserved for slaves, rebels, and common criminals. Cicero called it "the most cruel and most frightening of punishments" (<em>In Verrem</em> 2.5.165) and described it as so base that no Roman citizen should even have to look at it. To preach a crucified man as Lord and Savior in Rome required explicit counter-cultural assertion. Paul\'s "I am not ashamed" is a defiant challenge to the honor-shame calculus that governed Roman public life.</p><p>"First to the Jew, then to the Gentile" reflects the covenant-historical ordering: Israel received the Torah first and the gospel was preached first in Jerusalem. This priority is not privilege without accountability — as ch. 2 will show, it also means judgment comes first to Israel.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The citation of Hab 2:4 ("The righteous will live by faith") was already a significant interpretive touchstone in Second Temple Judaism. The Qumran community (1QpHab) applied it to the community of "doers of the law" — those who trust in the Teacher of Righteousness. Paul applies it to those who trust in the Messiah. The debate over whether <em>emunah</em> (Hab 2:4) means "faithfulness" (of God or the Messiah) or "faith" (of the believer) has roots in Second Temple interpretation, not just modern scholarship.</p><p>"A righteousness that is by faith from first to last" — <em>ek pisteōs eis pistin</em>, literally "from faith into faith." The phrase may indicate progressive deepening, the continuity of faith from OT to NT, or simply emphatic totality ("nothing but faith"). The point is that faith — not ethnic identity, not Torah observance — is the exclusive channel.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"The wrath of God is being revealed" — present tense, <em>apokalyptetai</em>, parallel to the "righteousness of God is revealed" in v. 17. Both revelations are happening now, simultaneously. The wrath Paul describes in vv. 18-32 is not primarily eschatological (future judgment) but present and social: it is visible in the moral disintegration that follows from idolatry. This "wrath" language draws on the OT tradition where God\'s wrath is his covenant faithfulness to justice — the necessary response of a holy God to the violation of the created order.</p><p>Paul\'s description of Gentile sin in 1:18-32 is deeply indebted to Wisdom of Solomon 11-15, a Jewish deuterocanonical text that Jewish readers would know well. Wisdom 14:12-27 makes the same argument: idolatry is the source of all moral disorder, including sexual immorality and social violence. Paul is not inventing this argument; he is deploying it to a Jewish audience who would nod along — before he turns it on them in ch. 2.</p>',

    "19": '<p>Paul argues that knowledge of God is available through creation — the "natural theology" argument. This follows a tradition in Hellenistic Jewish literature (Wisdom 13:1-9) that criticized Greek philosophical idolatry on the grounds that the philosophers could have known the true God from the created order but chose not to. Paul sharpens this: what can be known about God is not discovered by the diligent inquirer but "made plain" — disclosed — by God himself. The initiative is divine, not human.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"His eternal power and divine nature" — <em>dynamis</em> and <em>theiotēs</em>. The latter term (<em>theiotēs</em>) appears only here in the NT and carries a Hellenistic philosophical flavor — it is the quality of divinity rather than divinity itself (<em>theotēs</em>, Col 2:9). Paul is meeting his audience on familiar philosophical ground: Stoic and Platonic philosophy argued that the divine could be inferred from the ordered beauty of the cosmos. Paul agrees with the inference while insisting it has been willfully suppressed.</p><p>"Without excuse" (<em>anapologētous</em>) — the same word that an accused defendant would use to plead "I have no defense." Paul is framing creation-knowledge in forensic terms from the outset: this is not philosophy but accountability.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"Although they knew God, they neither glorified him nor gave thanks" — the failure is not intellectual but moral and relational. To "glorify" (<em>doxazō</em>) and "give thanks" (<em>eucharistō</em>) are the defining acts of the worshipping creature. Ancient Mediterranean religion was built on reciprocal gift exchange: gods gave benefits; humans offered sacrifice and praise in return. Paul says the Gentiles received God\'s gifts (creation, life) but failed to direct their gratitude to the right recipient.</p><p>"Their thinking became futile and their foolish hearts were darkened" — <em>emataiōthēsan</em> (became futile) draws on the LXX vocabulary of idolatry: <em>mataia</em> (empty, vain things) is the LXX term for idols in Jeremiah and the Psalms (e.g., Ps 31:6; Jer 2:5). Intellectual futility is framed as the cognitive consequence of moral failure, not its cause.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"Although they claimed to be wise, they became fools" — a direct inversion of the wisdom tradition. In Proverbs and Sirach, the fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom; those who reject God are by definition foolish. Paul targets the Greek philosophical tradition, which had produced enormous intellectual sophistication while maintaining polytheistic religion. Philosophers like Plato and Cicero did critique popular mythology, but they retained (or accommodated) civic religious practice. Paul regards this as the ultimate foolishness.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"Exchanged the glory of the immortal God for images" — this is a near-verbatim echo of Ps 106:20 ("They exchanged their Glory for an image of a bull that eats grass"), which refers to the golden calf at Sinai. Paul reframes the Gentile slide into idolatry as a repetition of Israel\'s worst moment — the substitution of a visible, controllable image for the invisible, uncontrollable God. Egyptian animal worship is in view ("birds and animals and reptiles"), a well-known target of Jewish polemic. Wisdom 11:15 makes the same point.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"God gave them over" (<em>paredōken</em>) — the verb appears three times (vv. 24, 26, 28) in a structural refrain. This is judicial language: God does not merely permit the slide into disorder; he actively hands people over to the consequences of their choices. The pattern echoes Ps 81:12 ("So I gave them over to their stubborn hearts to follow their own devices"). This is not abandonment in despair but judgment in which sin becomes its own punishment — the punishment fitting the crime is to be left with the consequences of the crime.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"They exchanged the truth about God for a lie" (<em>pseudei</em>) — the lie is idolatry itself: the claim that created things are divine. Paul is deploying the Jewish prophetic tradition (Jer 13:25; Isa 44:20) which described idols as lies and their worshippers as deceived. "Worshiped and served created things rather than the Creator" — the contrast between <em>latreuō</em> (serve/worship) directed to creation vs. Creator is the fundamental disorder. "Who is forever praised, amen" — Paul\'s doxological interjection is a synagogue reflex, the habitual response to any mention of God\'s name, inserting the worshipping community\'s proper response into the midst of an account of improper response.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"God gave them over to shameful lusts" — the second of the three judicial "hand-overs." Paul describes same-sex relations as a social symptom of the prior theological disorder (idolatry), not as an isolated moral category. In the argument\'s logic, disordered worship produces disordered relationships. This framing tracks with Jewish texts like Wisdom 14:12-27, which similarly link idolatry to sexual disorder. Paul does not engage the Greco-Roman philosophical debates about whether same-sex relations were natural or unnatural (Plato\'s <em>Symposium</em> defended them; other philosophers criticized them); he writes from within the Jewish scriptural tradition that treats procreative heterosexual marriage as the creational norm (Gen 1-2).</p>',

    "27": '<p>"Received in themselves the due penalty for their error" — Paul does not specify what this penalty is; the self-referential character of the punishment is the point. The "error" (<em>planē</em>) is the theological error of idolatry; the penalty is experienced "in themselves," suggesting the social and physical consequences of the disordered behavior. This fits the pattern of the three "hand-overs": the punishment is internal to the sin, not externally imposed. Ancient medicine also associated certain physical conditions with specific sexual practices, which some scholars think Paul may have in view, though the text does not specify.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"Did not think it worthwhile to retain the knowledge of God" — <em>ouk edokimasan ton theon echein en epignōsei</em>. The verb <em>dokimazō</em> means "to test and approve." The Gentiles tested the knowledge of God and found it inadequate — not worth retaining. God\'s judicial response is a play on the same word: since they rejected approved knowledge, he gave them over to a <em>adokimon</em> mind (a "failed," "rejected," "worthless" mind). The wordplay signals precise judicial correspondence: the judgment matches the crime in structure.</p>',

    "29": '<p>The vice list (vv. 29-31) follows a recognizable Hellenistic literary form. Stoic and Cynic philosophers compiled similar catalogues of moral failures to characterize degenerate social types. Paul\'s list is longer and more comprehensive than most NT parallels (cf. Gal 5:19-21; 1 Cor 6:9-10). The items are not random; they cluster around specific social disorders: anti-social aggression (evil, greed, malice), relational breakdown (strife, deceit, envy), verbal violence (gossip, slander), and family disorder (disobedience to parents). The catalogue is a portrait of a society that has lost the relational fabric that creation was designed to sustain.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"God-haters" (<em>theostygeis</em>) — the only occurrence of this word in the NT. It can mean either "hated by God" (passive) or "hating God" (active); context favors the active sense. "Insolent" (<em>hybristai</em>) — in Greek culture, <em>hybris</em> was the supreme social offense: treating an inferior as an inferior and a superior as an inferior, disregarding the proper order of honor. Applied to behavior toward God, it is the summary of the entire indictment in 1:18-32.</p>',

    "31": '<p>"No understanding, no fidelity, no love, no mercy" — the privative list describes the collapse of the specifically human social virtues: reason (<em>asynetos</em>), covenant-loyalty (<em>asynthetos</em>), natural affection (<em>astorgos</em>), and mercy (<em>aneleēmōn</em>). These are not random character flaws but the erosion of what makes human community possible. The privatives (<em>a-</em>) signal their absence where they should be present — a community of non-persons, so to speak.</p>',

    "32": '<p>"Although they know God\'s righteous decree that those who do such things deserve death, they not only continue but also approve of those who practice them" — the final intensification: not just doing but applauding. The cultural institution of public spectacles (<em>munera gladiatoria</em>, gladiatorial games) and the theatrical celebration of moral transgression in Roman entertainment culture is implicitly in view. Roman crowd culture explicitly celebrated violence, sexual license, and the humiliation of the weak. Paul\'s climactic charge is that participation in such celebrations is itself culpable — not just passive tolerance but active endorsement.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>Paul shifts rhetorical mode without announcement. The Greek literary form called <em>diatribē</em> (diatribe) was a classroom debate technique used by Stoic and Cynic philosophers — the teacher addresses an imaginary interlocutor (often introduced by "O man" or "you there") and voices objections that the students would naturally raise, then answers them. Paul deploys this technique throughout chs. 2-3. The identity of the imaginary judge in 2:1 is initially left open — Gentile moralist? Jewish observer? — but becomes progressively clear as a Torah-confident Jew by 2:17.</p><p>The logic is a trap: the reader who nodded approvingly through ch. 1\'s indictment of Gentile depravity now finds themselves standing in the dock. "At whatever point you judge another, you are condemning yourself" — the structure of self-condemnation was already present in the prophetic tradition (cf. Nathan\'s parable to David, 2 Sam 12:1-7: "You are the man!").</p>',

    "2": '<p>"God\'s judgment is based on truth" (<em>kata alētheian</em>) — judicial impartiality was a prized ideal in ancient justice systems, though honored more in theory than practice. Roman courts were notoriously susceptible to patronage and influence. The claim that God judges "according to truth" is a counter-claim against the systems of social protection that insulated elites from accountability. The Jewish scriptures repeatedly insist on God\'s impartiality (Deut 10:17; 2 Chr 19:7; Job 34:19).</p>',

    "3": '<p>The diatribal style continues with a rhetorical question: the imaginary moralist thinks possession of the law or of correct judgment insulates them from divine accountability. This was a genuine Second Temple Jewish temptation — assuming that knowing the right thing and condemning the wrong thing was itself a form of righteousness. Paul counters: God\'s knowledge is not limited to public behavior but extends to the inner life and private practice ("you who pass judgment do the same things").</p>',

    "4": '<p>"The riches of his kindness, forbearance and patience" — three terms clustering around God\'s patience: <em>chrēstotēs</em> (goodness/kindness), <em>anochē</em> (forbearance, the suspension of deserved punishment), and <em>makrothymia</em> (long-suffering, patience with provocation). In Second Temple Jewish theology, God\'s delay of judgment was interpreted as a gift of time for repentance, not as evidence that sin did not matter (cf. 2 Pet 3:9; Ecclus 5:4-7 warns against presuming on God\'s mercy). Paul is correcting a specific misreading: God\'s patience is not approval.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"Storing up wrath against yourself for the day of God\'s wrath" — the metaphor of accumulation draws on the wisdom tradition (Prov 3:34 LXX; Sirach 3:28) and reverses the normal desire to accumulate wealth and honor. Instead of storing up treasure, the unrepentant accumulate condemnation. "The day of God\'s wrath" is eschatological — the final judgment — but Paul presents it as the logical culmination of a process already underway. The "day of judgment" language is widespread in Second Temple literature (1 Enoch 22; 4 Ezra 7).</p>',

    "6": '<p>The quotation is from Ps 62:12 (LXX 61:13) — "He will repay each person according to their deeds" — a foundational principle that Paul deploys here to establish the universal standard before he applies it asymmetrically. This text was cited in early Jewish contexts (Prov 24:12; Job 34:11; Sirach 35:22) and was sufficiently common that Paul can introduce it simply with "it is written" — the standard citation formula for authoritative scripture.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The description of those who will receive eternal life — "those who by persistence in doing good seek glory, honor and immortality" — uses the vocabulary of the Greco-Roman honor quest. "Glory, honor, and immortality" were the supreme objects of elite Roman ambition, pursued through military achievement, political office, and memory preserved in monuments. Paul does not reject these aspirations but redirects their object: seeking them from God rather than human society. The reorientation of the honor system underlies much of Paul\'s ethical teaching.</p>',

    "8": '<p>"Self-seeking" (<em>eritheiai</em>) — the word originally described the behavior of a hired political worker who would work for any faction for pay, thus connoting factional self-interest over common good. By Paul\'s time it had acquired the sense of selfish ambition or contentiousness. "Reject the truth" and "follow evil" present the same exchange pattern as 1:25 — the willful substitution of falsehood for truth in the sphere of action.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"Trouble and distress for every human being who does evil: first for the Jew, then for the Gentile" — the ordering of "first for the Jew" in judgment echoes the "first for the Jew" in salvation (1:16). Greater privilege entails greater accountability, a principle rooted in the prophetic tradition (Amos 3:2: "You only have I chosen of all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you for all your sins"). Jewish election was never meant to be a shield against judgment but an intensification of moral responsibility.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"But glory, honor and peace for everyone who does good: first for the Jew, then for the Gentile" — the chiastic parallel with v. 9 confirms the structural symmetry: the same God who judges impartially also rewards impartially. "Peace" (<em>eirēnē</em>) here carries its full Hebrew <em>shalom</em> weight — comprehensive well-being and covenantal wholeness. The repetition of "first for the Jew" in both directions (blessing and judgment) maintains the covenant-historical priority while denying it as a protection from accountability.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"God does not show favoritism" (<em>ou gar estin prosōpolēmpsia para tō theō</em>) — <em>prosōpolēmpsia</em> (lit., "face-taking") translates the Hebrew <em>nasa panim</em> (lifting the face, i.e., showing partiality). The principle was embedded in Torah (Lev 19:15; Deut 1:17; 10:17) and developed extensively in Jewish ethical teaching. For Paul, it is not just a judicial principle but the theological ground for the universal scope of both judgment and salvation. A partial God would be a tribal God; the God of Israel is the God of all.</p>',

    "12": '<p>Paul introduces a crucial distinction: Gentiles who sin will be judged "apart from the law" (<em>anomōs</em>) — by a standard they were never given. Jews who sin will be judged "by the law" — by the standard they received and claimed to honor. This is not a two-tiered justice system but a single standard of accountability calibrated to knowledge. The principle was recognized in Second Temple ethics: "those who sin without knowledge sin without guilt" (cf. Num 15:22-31, the distinction between inadvertent and deliberate sin).</p>',

    "13": '<p>"It is not those who hear the law who are righteous in God\'s sight, but those who obey the law who will be declared righteous" — Paul counters a specific Second Temple Jewish assumption. In some streams of Second Temple thought, possession and study of the Torah was itself meritorious (cf. Sirach 24; Baruch 4:1). Paul insists the Torah is not a badge of status but a demand for performance. Hearing (<em>akroatai</em>) vs. doing (<em>poiētai</em>) — the distinction between the passive receipt and active obedience of law — echoes James 1:22-25 and the Sermon on the Mount (Matt 7:24-27).</p>',

    "14": '<p>The concept of Gentiles doing "by nature" (<em>physei</em>) what the law requires touches on Stoic natural law philosophy. The Stoics taught that a universal rational principle (<em>logos</em>) was inscribed in the cosmos and in human reason, accessible to all people regardless of their particular cultural tradition. Paul appropriates this concept: Gentiles who behave morally demonstrate that something morally ordering is at work in them, even without the Mosaic law. This is not a claim that Gentiles are naturally good but that they have access to a moral standard even apart from Torah.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"They show that the requirements of the law are written on their hearts" — the language echoes Jer 31:33, the new covenant promise of the law written on the heart. Paul is not saying Gentile moral behavior fulfills the new covenant; he is arguing more narrowly that it proves moral knowledge is available outside the Torah. "Conscience" (<em>syneidēsis</em>) was a significant term in Stoic moral philosophy — the inner witness that knows one\'s own actions for what they are. Seneca used it (roughly contemporary with Paul) to describe the interior judge that cannot be bribed. Paul adopts the Greek term but grounds it in creation rather than pure reason.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"This will take place on the day when God judges people\'s secrets through Jesus Christ, as my gospel declares" — the day of judgment is identified as the framework within which the present argument operates. "People\'s secrets" (<em>ta krypta tōn anthrōpōn</em>) — God\'s judgment reaches what human courts cannot: the inner life of motive, intention, and private action. The phrase "as my gospel declares" is a striking insertion — Paul claims that the gospel is not only about salvation but also about judgment, and that Jesus is the agent of both.</p>',

    "17": '<p>Having established the universal moral standard, Paul now turns to the Jewish reader directly. The diatribe intensifies: "if you call yourself a Jew" (<em>ei de su Ioudaios eponomazē</em>). The name "Jew" (from Judah) had become in the diaspora a term of religious identity and self-description, carrying enormous pride. "Rely on the law and boast in God" — these were genuine marks of Jewish identity. The Torah was Israel\'s distinctive gift (Deut 4:8: "What other nation is so great as to have such righteous decrees and laws?"). Paul does not deny the gift; he challenges the assumption that receipt of the gift confers status before God.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"Approve of what is superior" (<em>dokimazeis ta diapheronta</em>) — "test and approve the things that excel/differ." This refers to the capacity for moral discernment cultivated through Torah study and practice. In the synagogue tradition, the ability to distinguish the clean from the unclean, the permitted from the forbidden, the righteous from the wicked, was the mark of the learned teacher. Paul acknowledges this capacity; the question is whether it has issued in the corresponding practice.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"Convinced that you are a guide for the blind, a light for those in the dark" — the imagery is drawn from Israel\'s election as a light to the nations (Isa 42:6-7; 49:6). Isaiah describes the servant of the Lord as "a light for the Gentiles, to open eyes that are blind, to free captives from prison." The Jewish reader Paul addresses had applied this calling to themselves: Israel as the teaching people who would bring the Gentiles to knowledge of God. Paul does not dispute the calling; he questions whether those who claimed it lived up to it.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"The embodiment of knowledge and truth" (<em>tēn morphōsin tēs gnōseōs kai tēs alētheias en tō nomō</em>) — the Torah is "the form/embodiment" of knowledge and truth. <em>Morphōsis</em> can mean either "form" (the outward shape) or "embodiment" (the actual instantiation). The ambiguity is probably deliberate: Paul\'s critique will be that the Jewish teacher has the form without the substance, the shape without the reality.</p>',

    "21": '<p>Paul\'s rhetorical questions in vv. 21-23 follow the pattern of prophetic indictment. Amos, Isaiah, and Jeremiah repeatedly confronted Israel with the gap between their professed covenant loyalty and their actual behavior. The specific sins mentioned (stealing, adultery, temple robbery) are not random; they represent different categories of law: civil, sexual, and religious. The point is not that every Jewish teacher committed these acts but that the pattern of inconsistency was evident enough to be a live charge.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"You who abhor idols, do you rob temples?" — <em>hierosyleō</em> (rob temples) could refer to looting pagan temples (which Jewish sources sometimes condemned) or to the misappropriation of temple funds within Jewish religious practice. In the diaspora, Jewish communities sometimes depended on temple treasuries for communal welfare; misuse of these funds would be a form of sacrilege. The charge is not just hypocrisy in general but the specific irony of professing horror at idolatry while committing what amounted to desecration of their own sacred institutions.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"Do you dishonor God by breaking the law?" — the charge ties together the entire section: the Jew who boasts in the Torah (v. 17, 23) but breaks it dishonors the God whose name the Torah invokes. The indictment is not about Jewish law-observance being irrelevant but about the misuse of law as a source of ethnic pride rather than as a call to covenant faithfulness.</p>',

    "24": '<p>The quotation is from Isa 52:5 (LXX): "God\'s name is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you." The original context in Isaiah is the humiliation of Israel in exile — the nations, seeing Israel\'s defeat, concluded that Israel\'s God was weaker than the Babylonian gods. Paul applies the verse to the diaspora Jewish community whose behavior in the Roman world was creating a negative reputation for God. The logic is uncomfortable: Jewish misconduct in Rome was, in Paul\'s reading, a form of blasphemy against the God of Israel.</p>',

    "25": '<p>Circumcision was the foundational physical marker of Jewish covenant membership (Gen 17:10-14). It was required of all male Jews and of all male converts (<em>gerim</em>) to Judaism. In the second-temple period it was the most visible and controversial mark distinguishing Jews from Gentiles; Antiochus IV had prohibited it (1 Macc 1:48), and Jewish mothers had been martyred for circumcising their sons (1 Macc 1:60-61). The diaspora Jewish community defended circumcision intensely against Hellenistic pressure to abandon it.</p><p>Paul does not abolish circumcision\'s covenantal significance; he insists on its conditional character. The Torah itself made this argument: Lev 26:41 speaks of "uncircumcised hearts" among circumcised Israelites, and Deut 10:16 commands Israel to "circumcise the foreskin of your heart." Circumcision was always a sign of a prior covenant reality, not the reality itself.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"If those who are not circumcised keep the law\'s requirements, will they not be regarded as though they were circumcised?" — the counterfactual is deliberately provocative. Paul is not describing a common social reality (observant uncircumcised Gentiles were rare) but making a logical point: if the covenant requirement is moral performance, then covenant status follows performance, not the physical sign. This anticipates the Abraham argument in ch. 4, where Paul shows that Abraham was justified before circumcision (Gen 15:6 precedes Gen 17).</p>',

    "27": '<p>"The one who is not circumcised physically and yet obeys the law will condemn you" — the language of judgment is striking: a Gentile\'s obedience becomes juridical evidence against the disobedient Jew. This is not a claim that Gentile obedience is common or normative but a logical argument. The same rhetorical move appears in Matt 12:41-42, where Nineveh and the Queen of the South "condemn" Jesus\'s generation at the judgment — their faithful response becomes a witness against unfaithfulness.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"A person is not a Jew who is one only outwardly" (<em>en tō phanerō</em>, lit. "in what is visible/manifest") — Paul draws on a tradition within Jewish thought that distinguished between ethnic and spiritual Israel. The prophets had warned that physical descent from Abraham was no guarantee of covenant standing (Jer 9:26 condemns "all who are circumcised only in the flesh"; Ezek 44:7 speaks of those "uncircumcised in heart"). Paul is not inventing a new distinction but applying a prophetic one.</p>',

    "29": '<p>"Circumcision is circumcision of the heart, by the Spirit, not by the written code" — the phrase "circumcision of the heart" draws on Deut 30:6 ("The Lord your God will circumcise your hearts and the hearts of your descendants") and Jer 4:4 ("Circumcise yourselves to the Lord, circumcise your hearts"). Paul identifies the "Spirit" as the agent of this inner transformation, placing the new covenant fulfillment of Deut 30:6 within the present experience of the gospel.</p><p>"Such a person\'s praise is not from other people, but from God" — <em>epainos</em> (praise) plays on the etymology of the name Judah (<em>Yehudah</em>), derived from the Hebrew root <em>yadah</em> (to praise, to give thanks). A true Jew is one whose praise comes from God — a wordplay that only those familiar with the Hebrew tradition would catch.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>Paul shifts from argument to diatribal dialogue — he voices the Jewish reader\'s counter-objection. The advantage of being Jewish has just been called into question by the argument of ch. 2; the expected pushback is "then what\'s the point?" This kind of voiced objection is characteristic of the diatribe form; Paul throughout Romans voices objections more sharply than any actual opponent would, then answers them. The question is legitimate and Paul takes it seriously rather than dismissing it.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"The Jews have been entrusted with the very words of God" (<em>ta logia tou theou</em>) — the Hebrew scriptures were the supreme Advantage. In an oral-aural culture where texts were rare and literacy limited, possession of a body of sacred writing attributed to the creator of the universe was an extraordinary privilege. The Psalms celebrate this gift: "He has revealed his word to Jacob, his laws and decrees to Israel — he has done this for no other nation" (Ps 147:19-20). Paul does not deny this advantage but will show in 3:9ff that it did not exempt Israel from the universal indictment.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"What if some were unfaithful? Will their unfaithfulness nullify God\'s faithfulness?" — the diatribe continues. The question touches on a deep theological anxiety in Second Temple Judaism: how do the repeated failures of Israel — the golden calf, the apostasies of the kings, the exile — square with God\'s unconditional covenant promise to Abraham? Texts like Baruch, 4 Ezra, and the Qumran documents wrestle with this. Paul\'s answer draws on the logic of the OT itself: God\'s covenant faithfulness is not contingent on Israel\'s performance.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"Let God be true, and every human being a liar" — Paul cites Ps 51:4 (LXX 50:6): "that you may be proved right when you speak and prevail when you judge." In its original context, this is David\'s confession after his sin with Bathsheba — he acknowledges God\'s righteous judgment against him. Paul extracts the universal principle: in any dispute between God\'s word and human testimony, God wins. The forensic language ("prove right," "judge") fits the quasi-legal argument Paul is building toward the universal indictment of 3:9-20.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The diatribe speeds up through vv. 5-8, voicing and answering increasingly absurd objections. "If our unrighteousness brings out God\'s righteousness more clearly, is God unjust in bringing his wrath on us?" — this was a genuine theological problem in Judaism: if human sin provides the backdrop against which divine grace shines, does God have grounds to punish sin at all? Paul brackets the question with "(I am using a human argument)" — he acknowledges the logic is drawn from ordinary human reasoning, not from revelation, and thus has limited weight.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"If that were so, how could God judge the world?" — the argument from divine universality. In Second Temple Jewish theology, God\'s role as judge of the whole earth was foundational (Gen 18:25: "Will not the judge of all the earth do right?"). If God\'s justice were compromised by the logic of v. 5, his role as universal judge would be incoherent. The objection is answered by demolishing the premise, not by explaining how divine justice and human responsibility coexist — that comes in ch. 5-6.</p>',

    "7": '<p>A sharper version of the objection in v. 5: if my falsehood enhances God\'s glory, why am I condemned? This presses the "contrasting backgrounds" logic to its absurd conclusion — individual falsehood as a contribution to divine glory. Paul treats this as a species of rationalization, the kind of argument that makes bad behavior appear virtuous. The implied context is debates within the early church about whether sin "freed up" more grace (explicitly addressed in 6:1-2).</p>',

    "8": '<p>"Why not say — as some slanderously claim that we say — \'Let us do evil that good may result?\'" — Paul acknowledges that his gospel of grace had been caricatured as moral license by his opponents. This was a real charge against Pauline Christianity: if justification is by faith apart from works, what prevents libertinism? Paul\'s response here is simply to denounce both the doctrine and those who attributed it to him — the full answer comes in chs. 6-7. The phrase "their condemnation is just" is emphatic and formulaic — a moral verdict delivered without extended argument.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"Do we have any advantage? Not at all! For we have already made the charge that Jews and Gentiles alike are all under the power of sin" — Paul ties together the preceding argument. "Under the power of sin" (<em>hyph hamartian</em>, lit. "under sin") — sin is a power, an enslaving dominion, not merely a catalogue of individual acts. This personification of sin as an enslaving ruler was not merely rhetorical; it reflected the ancient understanding of cosmic powers (cf. 1 En 8-9, where angelic figures are responsible for teaching humanity wickedness).</p>',

    "10": '<p>Paul begins a string of OT citations (vv. 10-18) drawn from multiple books — Ps 14:1-3; Ps 53:1-3; Eccl 7:20; Ps 5:9; Ps 140:3; Ps 10:7; Isa 59:7-8; Ps 36:1. This technique of stringing texts together by theme was known in rabbinic interpretation as <em>haraz</em> (string of pearls or chain of texts) — a method of demonstrating that a single theological point is multiply attested in scripture. By weaving together texts from the Psalms, wisdom literature, and the prophets, Paul argues that the universal condemnation of humanity is the consistent testimony of the Hebrew canon, not Paul\'s personal opinion.</p><p>"There is no one righteous, not even one" — from Ps 14:1-3 (= Ps 53), which begins "The fool says in his heart, \'There is no God.\'" The Psalm\'s context is divine observation of universal moral failure. Paul quotes it as authoritative divine speech.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"There is no one who understands; there is no one who seeks God" — continuing Ps 14:2. The Psalm presents God looking down to see "if any understand, if any seek God" — and finding no one. The irony is that the very act of reading Romans is, for the reader, an instance of seeking God — which means the Psalm\'s sweeping negation is a literary and rhetorical device (consistent with its wisdom-poetry genre) rather than a literal claim about every individual. Paul uses it as a universal indictment of the human condition under sin, not a denial that any individual ever repents.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"All have turned away, they have together become worthless; there is no one who does good, not even one" — completing Ps 14:3 (LXX). "Become worthless" (<em>ēchreiōthēsan</em>) — the word suggests something gone rancid or functionally useless; it is used of spoiled food in some Greek texts. The image is of human moral capacity as corrupted by sin, not merely as failing in individual acts.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"Their throats are open graves; their tongues practice deceit. The poison of vipers is on their lips" — from Ps 5:9 and Ps 140:3. The anatomy of speech — throat, tongue, lips — is detailed: each organ of communication becomes an instrument of destruction. "Open graves" evokes the most extreme form of ritual uncleanness in Jewish law: contact with a corpse defiles. The throat-as-grave suggests that words flowing from it carry death and pollution.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"Their mouths are full of cursing and bitterness" — from Ps 10:7. In the Psalms\' context, this describes the wicked person who oppresses the vulnerable and who thinks God does not see. Paul uses it here as part of the universal picture rather than a description of a specific social type. The cataloguing of sins by the speech organs (vv. 13-14) was a recognized form in both Greek rhetoric (descriptions of flatterers, slanderers, demagogues) and Jewish wisdom literature.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"Their feet are swift to shed blood" — from Isa 59:7-8, a passage that Paul draws on through v. 17. Isaiah 59 is a national lament about the moral collapse of Israel — the prophet says "our iniquities have separated us from our God" (Isa 59:2). Paul applies Isaiah\'s indictment of Israel\'s sin to the universal human condition, enlarging the scope of an already sweeping text.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"Ruin and misery mark their paths" — continuing Isa 59:7. The word "ruin" (<em>suntrimma</em>) was used in military contexts for the wreckage left after a siege — a landscape of broken things. The catena\'s progression moves from the organs of speech (throat, tongue, lips, mouth, vv. 13-14) to the organs of action (feet, vv. 15-16) — the entire human body is implicated in the testimony of the scriptures against universal human sin.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"The way of peace they do not know" — completing Isa 59:8. The context in Isaiah is explicitly about the community\'s failure to maintain covenant justice and righteousness; the consequences are the absence of peace. <em>Shalom</em> in its full sense — the integrated well-being of covenant life — is inaccessible to those who have abandoned the moral structure on which it depends. Paul will return to the theme of peace (<em>eirēnē</em>) extensively in 5:1 (peace with God) and 14-15 (peace within the community).</p>',

    "18": '<p>"There is no fear of God before their eyes" — from Ps 36:1 (LXX 35:2). This verse closes the catena and supplies the theological explanation for all the preceding symptoms: the fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom (Prov 1:7; 9:10); its absence is the root from which all the catalogued sins grow. In the Hebrew wisdom tradition, "fear of God" was not psychological terror but the orientation of the whole life — cognitive, emotional, moral, practical — toward God\'s reality and authority.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"Whatever the law says, it says to those who are under the law, so that every mouth may be silenced and the whole world held accountable to God" — the rhetorical capstone of the indictment. The OT citations in vv. 10-18 were drawn from Israel\'s own scriptures; if those scriptures condemn Israel, they condemn everyone, since the law\'s voice reaches first to those within its covenant and by extension to all humanity. "Every mouth silenced" — the forensic image: in a court, when the defendant has no answer to the charge, they fall silent. All humanity is reduced to this silence before the divine tribunal.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"No one will be declared righteous in God\'s sight by the works of the law; rather, through the law we become conscious of our sin" — Paul echoes Ps 143:2 ("Do not bring your servant into judgment, for no one living is righteous before you"). The law\'s function, as Paul will develop in 7:7-13, is diagnostic rather than salvific: it reveals sin without resolving it. "Works of the law" (<em>erga nomou</em>) — a phrase that has generated significant modern debate (whether it means Torah observance in general or specifically identity markers like circumcision, food laws, and sabbath). Paul\'s argument requires the broader sense: no performance of any legal demand achieves the standing the law itself demands.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"But now apart from the law the righteousness of God has been made known" — <em>nyni de</em> (but now) is the great hinge of Romans and arguably of Paul\'s entire theology. It marks the eschatological turn: a new moment has arrived, distinct from everything that preceded it. "Apart from the law" does not mean "in contradiction to the law" — v. 21b immediately clarifies that the Law and the Prophets themselves testify to this righteousness. The law could not produce the righteousness it demanded; it has now been produced by a different means.</p><p>In the Second Temple period, many Jewish writers anticipated a decisive divine intervention that would transform the moral situation of humanity — what Paul is describing in vv. 21-26 is that this transformation has arrived in Christ\'s death and resurrection, though in a form no one had predicted.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"This righteousness is given through faith in Jesus Christ to all who believe. There is no difference between Jew and Gentile" — the "no difference" (<em>ou gar estin diastolē</em>) deliberately echoes 2:11 ("God does not show favoritism"). The symmetry is structural: in ch. 2, no difference in accountability; in ch. 3, no difference in access to righteousness. The Gentile-inclusion is not an afterthought but the logical entailment of the universal indictment: if all are under sin equally, and if righteousness comes through faith equally, then ethnicity is irrelevant to covenant standing.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"For all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God" — <em>husterountai tēs doxēs tou theou</em>. "Fall short" is a present indicative — an ongoing condition, not merely a past act. "The glory of God" in Jewish thought encompassed both God\'s radiance (the shekinah of the temple) and the human vocation to image God. Some Second Temple texts (4 Ezra 7:122; 1QS 4:23; CD 3:20) speak of the "glory" as a primordial dignity lost at the fall and to be restored in the new age. Paul may be invoking this tradition: to "fall short of God\'s glory" is to fall short of what humanity was created to be, not only to fail to reach a distant standard.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"Justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus" — "redemption" (<em>apolytrōsis</em>) is release-through-payment, the language of manumission (buying a slave\'s freedom) and of ransom (paying for a prisoner\'s release). In the LXX it is used for the Exodus — God\'s great act of redemptive release from slavery in Egypt (Exod 6:6; Deut 7:8; 15:15). Paul presents Christ\'s death as the new Exodus: liberation from the slavery of sin at a cost, paid by God rather than by the enslaved. The word "freely" (<em>dōrean</em>) emphasizes that no contribution is demanded from the enslaved party.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement" (<em>hilastērion</em>) — the Greek word <em>hilastērion</em> is used in the LXX as the technical term for the <em>kapporeth</em>, the golden lid of the Ark of the Covenant — the "mercy seat" (Exod 25:17-22; Lev 16:14-15). On Yom Kippur (the Day of Atonement), the high priest entered the Holy of Holies once a year and sprinkled the blood of the sin offering on the mercy seat, making atonement for Israel\'s accumulated sins. This was the most sacred act in Israel\'s annual liturgical calendar — hidden from all eyes, performed in secret behind the veil.</p><p>Paul\'s application is striking in its reversals: where the mercy seat was hidden in the Holy of Holies, Christ was "set forth publicly" (<em>proetheto</em>) — displayed in crucifixion for all to see. Where the blood was sprinkled ritually on the golden lid, Christ\'s blood was shed in historical execution. The one annual sacrifice becomes the once-for-all sacrifice (cf. Heb 9:12). Paul\'s Jewish readers would have recognized the Day of Atonement imagery immediately.</p><p>"Because in his forbearance he had left the sins committed beforehand unpunished" — the accumulated sins of the entire OT period, atoned for repeatedly but never finally, are now addressed by the cross. The cross demonstrates that God was never simply overlooking sin; his patience was holding open the space for the definitive atonement that was coming.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"To be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus" — the theological tension Paul resolves: how can God be both perfectly just (requiring that sin be punished) and the one who acquits sinners? The cross is the answer: in Christ, God bore the weight of sin\'s condemnation himself, so that justification is not a compromise of justice but its satisfaction. This is the logical center of Paul\'s argument. The Second Temple period offered multiple theories of atonement (martyrological, representative, substitutionary elements appear in 4 Maccabees, the Qumran texts, and apocalyptic literature); Paul synthesizes these in light of Christ\'s specific historical death.</p>',

    "27": '<p>"Where, then, is boasting? It is excluded" (<em>ekkleiō</em>) — the verb means to shut out, to bar from entry. Boasting (<em>kauchēsis</em>) in the Torah and in Jewish identity was not mere arrogance but a form of legitimate covenant confidence — the recognition that being entrusted with God\'s law was a gift and a calling. Paul does not attack this attitude as such; he argues that the faith-righteousness of 3:21-26 structurally excludes it, because faith is precisely the posture of receiving rather than achieving.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"A person is justified by faith apart from the works of the law" — the compressed thesis statement that will dominate Reformation-era debates. "Works of the law" (<em>erga nomou</em>) — whether this means all law-keeping or specifically the ethnic-identity markers (circumcision, food laws, calendar observances) that divided Jew from Gentile is a major scholarly debate. Paul\'s argument here points toward the broader sense: any form of legal performance, since the law\'s function is to condemn rather than to justify (v. 20).</p>',

    "29": '<p>"Or is God the God of Jews only? Is he not the God of Gentiles too?" — the monotheism argument. Jewish theology was strictly monotheistic (Deut 6:4, the Shema: "Hear O Israel, the Lord our God, the Lord is one"). One God logically entails one standard, one judge, and one means of right-standing. If God were only the God of Jews, he could have a Jewish-specific method of justification; if he is the God of all humanity, there must be a universal access point. Paul\'s radical claim is that faith is precisely that universal access point, which is why it makes the gospel available to Gentiles without requiring them to become Jews first.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"Since there is only one God, who will justify the circumcised by faith and the uncircumcised through that same faith" — the Shema (Deut 6:4) becomes the theological foundation for Gentile inclusion. The distinction between "by faith" (<em>ek pisteōs</em>) and "through faith" (<em>dia tēs pisteōs</em>) for circumcised and uncircumcised respectively has generated debate; most interpreters see it as stylistic variation rather than a theological distinction. The point is the unity of the means: one God, one faith, one people — the logical entailment of Jewish monotheism applied to its full scope.</p>',

    "31": '<p>"Do we, then, nullify the law by this faith? Not at all! Rather, we uphold the law" (<em>nomon histanomen</em>, lit. "we cause the law to stand") — Paul anticipates the obvious charge that his faith-righteousness abolishes the Torah. His answer is more compressed here than the extended argument of ch. 7; the grounds for "upholding" the law through faith will include: (a) the law itself testified to faith-righteousness (3:21; the Abraham argument of ch. 4); (b) faith fulfills the law\'s moral demand through the Spirit (8:4); (c) the law\'s diagnostic function is confirmed, not dissolved, by the gospel. This verse serves as a bridge to the Abraham argument that follows in ch. 4.</p>'
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'romans')
